Project Goal

This project implements an event-driven Azure Data Engineering pipeline using
Azure Data Factory, Databricks, Delta Lake, and the Medallion Architecture (Bronze Silver Gold).

The pipeline is triggered automatically on file upload to Azure Blob Storage and processes
a single incoming data file end-to-end from raw ingestion to a curated dataset stored
in Azure SQL Database for analytics and reporting.

The solution follows modern lakehouse and data governance practices, leveraging
Databricks Unity Catalog for centralized access control over curated data.

The goal of this project is to demonstrate production-oriented Data Engineering skills, including:

  • event-driven orchestration with Azure Data Factory
  • distributed data processing using PySpark
  • Delta Lake ACID layers and Medallion Architecture
  • centralized data governance using Unity Catalog
  • secure access via external locations (no credentials in code)
  • data validation, transformations, and KPI-ready outputs
  • clean, maintainable, and scalable pipeline design

High-Level Architecture

Below is the high-level architecture of the pipeline:

Flow overview:

  1. File uploaded to Azure Blob Storage (event trigger)
  2. Azure Data Factory pipeline starts automatically
  3. Databricks notebook processes data using Medallion Architecture
  4. Gold data written to Delta Lake
  5. Curated dataset copied into Azure SQL Database
  6. Source file cleanup after successful processing

This architecture enables fully automated, scalable, and governed data processing.

Azure Data Factory Pipeline

The pipeline is fully automated and event-driven.

Pipeline Steps:

  1. Blob Storage Trigger starts pipeline when a new file is uploaded
  2. Databricks Notebook Activity executes PySpark ETL (Bronze Silver Gold)
  3. Copy Activity loads curated Gold data into Azure SQL Database
  4. Cleanup Step deletes processed source file to prevent reprocessing

The pipeline is designed for idempotent, production-style execution.

Data Governance & Connectivity

This project follows modern cloud governance best practices.

Databricks workspace & metastore:

Key principles:

  • Unity Catalog manages access to curated data
  • External Locations define governed access to storage paths
  • No secrets or credentials stored in notebooks
  • Permissions enforced centrally at the metastore level
  • Clean separation between storage, processing, and access control

This setup reflects enterprise-grade lakehouse governance.

Bronze Layer Raw Ingestion

The Bronze layer stores raw-but-validated data in Delta format.

What happens in Bronze:

  • Read uploaded source file from Blob Storage
  • Write raw data to Bronze Delta tables

Data is preserved as close to the original source as possible.

Silver Layer Cleaning & Transformation

The Silver layer produces clean, normalized, and validated data.

Processing steps:

  • Read data from Bronze Delta tables
  • Data cleaning (null handling, deduplication)
  • Type casting & schema enforcement
  • Business rule validation
  • Data normalization for analytics
  • Write curated dataset to Silver Delta tables

At this stage, the data is reliable and analytics-ready.

Gold Layer Curated Output

The Gold layer contains final, consumption-ready data.

Gold processing:

  • Read data from Silver Delta tables
  • Final transformations & formatting
  • Overwrite Gold Delta table with curated output
  • Prepare schema for downstream systems

The Gold table acts as the single source of truth.

Data Sink Azure SQL Database

The final Gold dataset is loaded into Azure SQL Database using an ADF Copy Activity.

Purpose:

  • Enable easy access for BI tools and applications
  • Provide relational, query-optimized storage
  • Support reporting and downstream analytics

Logging & Observability

Basic logging is implemented inside the Databricks notebook:

  • Read start / success
  • Transformation completion
  • Write success / failure
  • Error handling and exceptions

This enables traceability and easier debugging.

Possible Enhancements

  • Add metadata-driven ingestion (multiple files / folders)
  • Introduce data quality checks (e.g. Great Expectations)
  • Parameterize pipeline for multiple datasets
  • Add monitoring & alerting for pipeline failures
  • Implement incremental or CDC-based processing
  • Optimize parallel execution for larger data volumes
